# MIDAS architecture (`architecture.mdc`)

Authoritative design rules for MIDAS. Apply to every technical decision.

Canonical diagram: [Miro board](https://miro.com/app/board/uXjVGnrWh1o=/). If your change contradicts the diagram, flag the discrepancy to the user.

## Non-negotiable principles

1. **Private-by-default.** All workloads run in VPC `vpc-0c4d673f3e95a93eb` (CIDR `10.72.134.0/23`). No public endpoints, public IPs, Internet Gateways, or NAT Gateways. All AWS API calls use VPC interface endpoints (PrivateLink) with Private DNS. Egress uses Transit Gateway `tgw-0ec391fa73943d562`.
2. **Single region `us-east-1`.** No multi-region, no cross-region replication, no fallback regions.
3. **AI / Gen-AI first.** Prefer managed AWS AI/ML services (Bedrock, SageMaker) accessed via PrivateLink. All AI traffic stays inside the VPC.
4. **Stateless compute, managed state.** EKS pods and ECS tasks must be stateless. Persist to RDS/Aurora, ElastiCache, S3, or OpenSearch. Never write durable state to container disk.
5. **Event-driven by default.** Use SQS, SNS, or EventBridge for async or long-running work. Use synchronous request/response only when latency requires it.

## Layered architecture

| Layer | Typical components |
|---|---|
| Presentation / API | Internal ALB, REST/GraphQL APIs, EKS-hosted services |
| Orchestration | LangChain / LangGraph agents, Step Functions, EKS workloads |
| AI / ML | Bedrock, vector stores, SageMaker endpoints |
| Data | S3, RDS/Aurora, ElastiCache, OpenSearch |
| Platform / Infra | EKS, ECS, VPC, KMS, Secrets Manager, CloudWatch |
| CI/CD | Jenkins, ECR, Terraform, Helm |

Every change must identify which layer(s) it affects and preserve cross-layer contracts (APIs, schemas, events).

## Component design rules

- **APIs.** Define a contract (OpenAPI, Protobuf, or documented schema) before implementing. Version from day one (`/v1/`, `/v2/`). Intra-cluster calls use Kubernetes service DNS; never hardcode IPs.
- **Data ownership.** Each data store has one owning service. Other services go through the owner's API. Document any shared-read exception.
- **Security boundaries.** Each layer has its own security group. Ingress is minimal and only from the layer above. Use IRSA or Secrets Manager; never embed credentials in code or images.

## Stop and ask the user before

- Adding a new AWS service type not already in the architecture.
- Creating any public endpoint.
- Adding a new data store or changing a data store's owning service.
- Changing the AI/ML model provider or inference pattern (for example moving off Bedrock).
- Introducing cross-region resources or traffic.
- Any change that contradicts the Miro diagram.

For each of the above, recommend an ADR at `docs/adr/NNNN-<short-title>.md` (format: Title, Status, Context, Decision, Consequences).

